<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Clock Violations and Stalling</h2>

<p>Tournament Scrabble uses chess clocks with 25 minutes per player. Clock manipulation — deliberately running an opponent's time or exploiting technical malfunctions — has caused multiple disputes.</p>

<div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20">
    <p class="text-purple-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">⏱️ Deliberate Stalling</p>
    <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Players with a lead have been accused of playing slowly to force opponents into time pressure. Rules now penalise 10 points per minute overtime.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20">
    <p class="text-purple-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">⏱️ Clock Button Disputes</p>
    <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Accusations of hitting the clock before fully releasing a tile, or "hovering" to confuse opponents about turn completion, prompted clearer rules about turn endings.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Notable Challenge Controversies</h2>

<p>The challenge system — where players risk a turn to dispute a word — has produced dramatic moments. Strategic "phoney" plays (playing fake words hoping opponents won't challenge) walk a fine ethical line.</p>

<div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Phoney plays:</span> Playing a non-word intentionally is legal in Scrabble — if unchallenged, it stays. Top players routinely bluff with obscure-looking combinations, creating ethical grey areas about sportsmanship.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Double challenge rule:</span> Under NASPA rules, a failed challenge costs the challenger their turn. This asymmetry has been criticised for discouraging legitimate challenges and rewarding bluffing.</p>
  </div>
</div>

